1821 Park Avenue, N. E. corner 125th Street, at that time known as 2303 Fourth Avenue, an old frame house, which stood on this site till about 1900, when it was replaced by 12-story Hamilton Building -later known as Lee Building.

Harlem Hall (Nos. 117-125).
1904.

722400f-a.text: Park Avenue, at S.W. corner of 125th Street, Hotel Naomi. August 2, 1927. P. L. Sperr.

715373f-a.text: 79-81 East 125th Street, adjoining and at the N.W. corner of Park Ave. The Mt. Morris Branch of the Corn Exchange Bank is shown employing the lower floors of corner building (No. 81), also known as No. 1820 Park Ave. A portion of the 125th Street Station of the N.Y.C.R.R., is also shown on Park Ave. June 24, 1934. P. L. Sperr.

715371f-a.text:
East 125th Street, east from, but not including Park Ave. Notice the Harlem Grand Theatre, (Nos. 117-125) and Proctor's 125th Street Theatre, (Nos. 112-118) facing each other on opposite sides of the street.
July 24, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.

715370f-b.text:
The Hotel Naomi, 125th Street at the S.W. corner of Park Ave. This hotel, facing on Park Ave., is composed of five brick houses joined together. Its sale was recently delayed to locate the owner
of a four-inch strip through the centre.
August 2, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
The same, from a different angle.
July 24, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.
